06288nam a22008895i 9789812307101DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20062006si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898123071017 a10.1355/97898123071012doi  a(DE-B1597)492211  a(OCoLC)1041984463  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aPOL0370002bisacsh04a355.0330522200aAsian Security Reassessed /ced. by Stephen Hoadley, Jurgen Ruland. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (400 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbout the Contributors -- tList of Abbreviations -- tPreface -- tPart One. Approaches to Asian Security -- t1. The Evolution of Security Thinking: An Overview -- tPart Two. Security Management by Asian States and Regional Institutions -- t2. Asia from Colonialism to Culturalism -- t3. Japan and East Asian Regional Security -- t4. China’s Security Strategy and Policies -- t5. United States Security Policies in Asia -- t6. Regional Security Institutions: ASEAN, ARF, SCO and KEDO -- tPart Three. Non-Traditional Challenges to Asian Security -- t7. Weapons Proliferation in Asia -- t8. Conflicts over Natural Resources and the Environment -- t9. Ethnic Conflict, Separatism and Terrorism -- t10. Irregular Migration as a Security Issue -- t11. Globalization and Asian Financial Insecurity -- t12. Challenges to Human Rights and Civil Liberties -- tPart Four. New Concepts of Asian Security -- t13. Asian Security as a Global Public Good -- t14. Communities and Security in Pacific Asia -- t15. Traditionalism and Change in the Asian Security Discourse -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book traces changes in the concept of security in Asia from realist to cooperative, comprehensive, and human security approaches, and assesses a number of policy alternatives to management of both old and new security threats. It surveys not only orthodox security threats such as tensions between regional powers or armed ethnic antagonists but also new sources of anxiety such as resource scarcity, economic instability, irregular migration, community fragmentation, and international terrorism. Security policies of major powers such as China, Japan, and the United States, and the moderating roles of regional organizations such as ASEAN, ARF, SCO, and KEDO are evaluated in historical and contemporary perspectives. Contributors proffer policy-relevant insights where appropriate. The book concludes that traditional security approaches remain valid but need to be adapted to the new challenges, and offers suggestions for incorporating fresh Asian security perceptions into the agendas of policy-makers, analysts, and scholars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNational securityzAsia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Terrorism.2bisacsh1 aDosch, Jörn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilson, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaacke, Jürgen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoadley, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoadley, Stephen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJetschke, Anja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyon, Rod, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Bernd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMikic, Mia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuland, Jurgen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRüland, Jürgen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.